======================================================================
			ASSIGNMENT CFJ 827
Player Favor violated 1497 when he posted to the Public Forum the message 
entitled "Apothecary's Romance".
======================================================================
Judge:		elJefe
Judgement:	

Eligible:	Andre, Chuck, Coco, Dave Bowen, elJefe, favor, KoJen, 
		Michael, Morendil, SaltWater, Steve, Vanyel, Zefram

Not Eligible:	
Caller:		Oerjan
Barred:		
On Hold:	

Effects:	elJefe gains 5 Points for speedy Judgement
		favor must issue a Formal Apology

======================================================================

History:
  Called by Oerjan, 8 Nov 1995, 17:11 +0100 (MET)
  Assigned to elJefe, 8 Nov 1995, 17:50 MET
  Judged TRUE by elJefe, 9 Nov 1995, 12:47 -0500

======================================================================

Arguments: none

======================================================================

Judgement:   TRUE

Reasons:

|favor| claims the statements in the message (EXHIBIT A) were not "presented 
as correct", since the Subject line "Apothecary's Romance" should have alerted
us to the fact that the statements were not factual.

I reject this, as common sense and Game Custom require at least an initial
presumption that an unadorned statement, without preamble or explanation, 
is to be taken at face value.  Several players did so take it (though 
believing it mistaken), and if it had been something else, e.g. a Mark 
transfer, it could have taken effect regardless of the Subject line.

It would be possible to judge FALSE if |favor| merely posted the statements
with reckless disregard as to their truth or falsity. However, the judge's
Examination of the Defendant indicates that this was not the case.

Others have tried to claim that an attempted game move is not the same
as "presenting information".  I reject this also.  A statement of the
form "I hereby cause a transfer ..." certainly presents information to 
the Recordkeepors for whatever currency is involved.

Again, had this been a legal transfer, it could have taken effect. 
It would take place at the time it is "reported" (Rule 1472).  It's hard to 
see how one can "report" a transaction without "presenting information."

This is not to say that all attempted illegal moves are violations of 1497.
Only those in which the initiator emself disbelieved the information reported.


----------------------------------------
Injunction:

Tempering Justice with Mercy, I decline to issue any Injunction containing
Prescribed Words for the required Formal Apology.  The Formal Apology
is required, but the words I leave up to the ingenuity and creativity
of the Defendant.

- elJefe, Judge


